===Etymology===
* {{sense|lodging}} First attested in 1600.
* From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|accommodatio|accommodātiō|adjustment, accommodation, compliance|lang=la}}, from {{term|accommodo|accommodō|adapt, put in order|lang=la}}.
* Compare French {{term|accommodation|lang=fr}}.
* {{suffix|accommodate|tion}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˌkɒm.ə.ˈdeɪ.ʃən/}}
* {{rhymes|eɪʃən}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

#{{senseid|en|lodging}}{{context|chiefly|British|usually|a mass noun}} [[lodging|Lodging]] in a [[dwelling]] or similar living quarters afforded to travellers in hotels or on cruise ships, or prisoners, etc.
# {{context|countable|uncountable|followed by ''to''}} The act of fitting or adapting, or the state of being fitted or adapted; adaptation; adjustment.
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|Sir Matthew Hale}}
#*: The organization of the body with '''accommodation''' to its functions.
# {{context|countable|uncountable}} Willingness to accommodate; obligingness.
# Whatever supplies a want or affords ease, refreshment, or convenience; anything furnished which is desired or needful; -- often in the plural; as, the '''accommodations''' -- that is, lodgings and food -- at an inn
#* {{rfquotek|Sir W. Scott}}
# {{context|countable|uncountable}} Adjustment of differences; state of agreement; reconciliation; settlement; compromise.
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay}}
#*: To come to terms of '''accommodation'''.
# {{context|countable}} The application of a writer's language, on the ground of analogy, to something not originally referred to or intended.
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|William Paley}}
#: Many of those quotations from the Old Testament were probably intended as nothing more than '''accommodations'''.
# {{context|countable|commerce}} A loan of money.
# {{context|countable|commerce}} An accommodation bill or note.
# {{context|countable|legal}} An offer of [[substitute]] [[goods]] to [[fulfill]] a [[contract]], which will bind the [[purchaser]] if [[accepted]]
# {{context|countable|physiology|biology}} The adaptation or adjustment of an organism, organ, or part.
# {{context|countable|medical}} The adjustment of the eye to a change of the distance from an observed object.

